This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Signal Processing (cs.SP) sub-categories. However, since the paper focuses on building algorithmically closed-form lower and upper bounds on these measures, it is more likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses techniques such as Monte Carlo stochastic integration and approximation, which are commonly used in Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Data Science (cs.DS) sub-categories. The paper also presents experiments on various types of mixtures, which suggests that it could belong to the Scientific Computing (cs.SI) or Numerical Analysis (cs.NA) sub-categories.
